<sect1><title>Administrator form</title>

<para>Start page of the web interface as an administrator authenticated:
<inlinegraphic entityref="testadministrator-main" fileref="testadministrator-main" scale="50"></inlinegraphic>
</para>

<para>Apart from the actions the maintainer group can perform, the administrator
group can also administer basic server settings. The hostname and the domain
name of the E-Mail domain can be set in the server menue. Note that changes 
within those settings directly affect the mail transport system and can result 
in delivery problems of E-Mails.
</para>

<para>
You may set the hostname of the kolab environment in the kolab 
web administration interface. This does not change the hostname of the 
underlaying operating system though. The primary purpose of this setting is 
to enable the administration to easily tell all kolab components about the 
hostname to be used for the kolab groupware solution. This is due to two 
potential things: Firstly it may happen that the hostname of the machine did 
change since the initial installation and therefor kolab has to be made aware 
of this fact. Secondly a unix like OS may have several hostnames and via the 
kolab webinterface you may tell kolab which hostname to use.
Last but not least: Please be aware of the fact that the kolab webinterface 
s not intended to adminstrate a unix operating system but only to administrate 
the kolab groupware component. If you are interested in a web based os 
administration tool you may have a look at webmin or others. This operating
system agnostic approach is due to the platform independent nature of the kolab
solution.
</para>

<para>
<inlinegraphic entityref="testadministrator-server" fileref="testadministrator-server" scale="50"></inlinegraphic>
</para>

<para>The administration of the two groups administrator and maintainer is
possible from within the menues Administrator or Maintainer. Accounts
within the groups can be created or removed. As those accounts do not possess 
own E-Mail addresses only few information is needed to specify an account. These
credentials are first and last name, a password and a uid.
</para>

<para>
<inlinegraphic entityref="testadministrator-maintnr" fileref="testadministrator-maintnr" scale="50"></inlinegraphic>
<inlinegraphic entityref="testadministrator-create-admin" fileref="testadministrator-create-admin" scale="50"></inlinegraphic>
</para>

<para>Although the Kolab server has the ability to interoperate with legacy
clients this behaviour can be turned off. The preferred services of
the Kolab server are: POP3S, IMAPS, SIEVE and HTTPS. In legacy mode the services
POP3, IMAP, FTP and HTTP are also supported. Within the menue services of the
web interface an administrator can disable some or all of the legacy services.
</para>

<para>
<inlinegraphic entityref="testadministrator-services" fileref="testadministrator-services" scale="50"></inlinegraphic>
</para>

<para>To ensure the correct operation of the Kolab server an administrator can
take a look at the system logs from within the Kolab log menue.
</para>

